00:02:19.270 --> 00:02:20.870
&gt;&gt; Joyce Carol Oates: Yes, yes.

00:02:20.870 --> 00:02:23.670
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: It's called
Soul at the White Heat,

00:02:23.670 --> 00:02:26.050
Inspiration Obsession
and the Writing Life.

00:02:26.050 --> 00:02:27.820
Now that title Soul at
the White Heat comes

00:02:27.820 --> 00:02:29.560
from a Emily Dickinson poem.

00:02:29.560 --> 00:02:31.260
&gt;&gt; Joyce Carol Oates: Yes
it's an Emily Dickinson poem,

00:02:31.260 --> 00:02:35.190
typically very passionate Emily
Dickinson poem that it's really

00:02:35.190 --> 00:02:37.060
about the making of poetry.

00:02:37.060 --> 00:02:41.280 position:56%
You dare you see a soul at the white
heat, you know sort of come closer

00:02:41.280 --> 00:02:45.950
and see the artist at
his or her creativity.

00:02:45.950 --> 00:02:47.570
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: And
what is that phrase mean

00:02:47.570 --> 00:02:49.700
in your own life and your own work?

00:02:49.700 --> 00:02:51.790
&gt;&gt; Joyce Carol Oates: Well I think
it's something that sort of ran

00:02:51.790 --> 00:02:55.690
through my mind, dare you
see a soul at the white heat,

00:02:55.690 --> 00:02:59.360
first of all that seems to
suggest that we have souls,

00:02:59.360 --> 00:03:04.000
that we're spiritual beings, that
there's something almost impersonal

00:03:04.000 --> 00:03:06.910
and transcendental about
us, that's not merely petty

00:03:06.910 --> 00:03:10.250
and media, but something deeper.

00:03:10.250 --> 00:03:14.930
All those things that I think come
into play when we are imagining

00:03:14.930 --> 00:03:18.810 position:56%
or we're immersing imagination we
sort of move away from the pettiness

00:03:18.810 --> 00:03:23.040
and transience of life into
something more abiding and deeper,

00:03:23.040 --> 00:03:26.510
that has a kind of communal
feeling with other people.

00:03:26.510 --> 00:03:28.270
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: In that
collection you mention that one

00:03:28.270 --> 00:03:30.910
of the first short story
writers that really turned you

00:03:30.910 --> 00:03:33.540
on to literature was
Ernest Hemingway?

00:03:33.540 --> 00:03:34.840
&gt;&gt; Joyce Carol Oates: Oh yes.

00:03:34.840 --> 00:03:36.150
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: Which
surprises me, I love your books,

00:03:36.150 --> 00:03:39.030
I don't think of you
like Ernest Hemingway.

00:03:39.030 --> 00:03:40.650
You seem very different.

00:03:40.650 --> 00:03:41.950
Very different.

00:03:41.950 --> 00:03:43.380
&gt;&gt; Joyce Carol Oates: Well I
always teach Hemingway particularly

00:03:43.380 --> 00:03:45.480
at the start of a writing workshop

00:03:45.480 --> 00:03:47.200
and then the beginning
of a semester.

00:03:47.200 --> 00:03:52.420
A quintessential Hemingway
story like Indian Camp or Hills

00:03:52.420 --> 00:03:57.440
like White Elephants it has
almost like a skeletal structure,

00:03:57.440 --> 00:04:03.470 position:56%
it's very pure and very clear, often
characters don't even have names.

00:04:03.470 --> 00:04:06.660
Maybe just a young
man or a young woman

00:04:06.660 --> 00:04:10.230
and they have an intense dialogue
and their lives are changed.

00:04:10.230 --> 00:04:12.640
And maybe one or two pages,

00:04:12.640 --> 00:04:16.360
three pages long it's something
very beautifully wrought,

00:04:16.360 --> 00:04:23.380
almost a kind of calligraphy,
beautiful, beautiful writing

00:04:23.380 --> 00:04:27.610
of selection and emphasis.

00:04:27.610 --> 00:04:32.310
Rather than a maximum of most
that has a lot of detail,

00:04:32.310 --> 00:04:35.100
this is a minimus art
that is very beautiful.

00:04:35.100 --> 00:04:39.070
So for a writer who is
more of a maximalist

00:04:39.070 --> 00:04:41.910
who still have that
skeletal structure.

00:04:41.910 --> 00:04:46.020
I mean it may be three pages in
Hemingway but if you're a writer

00:04:46.020 --> 00:04:50.480 position:56%
who wants to put more of the world
in and describe people and so forth,

00:04:50.480 --> 00:04:54.920
you basically still need that
structure and that trajectory

00:04:54.920 --> 00:04:56.740
of peoples lives being changed.

00:04:56.740 --> 00:04:58.040
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: You start
that way with a novel?

00:04:58.040 --> 00:05:00.700
Do you have it that paired down?

00:05:00.700 --> 00:05:03.630
&gt;&gt; Joyce Carol Oates: I always have
the ending, I have the beginning

00:05:03.630 --> 00:05:06.510
and the trouble is the middle.

00:05:06.510 --> 00:05:09.540
[ Laughter ]

00:05:09.540 --> 00:05:13.740
Yeah. I'd like to have a title,
a beginning and an ending.

00:05:13.740 --> 00:05:17.760 position:56%
The title, the title, the
beginning and the ending have a kind

00:05:17.760 --> 00:05:22.740
of triangular architectural
relationship so it's

00:05:22.740 --> 00:05:25.410
like a center of gravity
that's fixed.

00:05:25.410 --> 00:05:27.640
And you know what you're doing,

00:05:27.640 --> 00:05:30.500
as you go through the novel
you have a destination

00:05:30.500 --> 00:05:32.330
and you know what you're doing.

00:05:32.330 --> 00:05:33.630
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: Your
publisher doesn't come along

00:05:33.630 --> 00:05:34.930 position:56%
and say no Joyce we want this title,

00:05:34.930 --> 00:05:37.850
this title didn't pan well
with our test audience?

00:05:37.850 --> 00:05:42.160
&gt;&gt; Joyce Carol Oates: Well
that hasn't happened yet.

00:05:42.160 --> 00:05:44.760
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: In one of those
essays you write the most serious

00:05:44.760 --> 00:05:48.580
and productive artists are
haunted by their material.

00:05:48.580 --> 00:05:49.880
&gt;&gt; Joyce Carol Oates: Yes.

00:05:49.880 --> 00:05:51.180
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: Haunted, were
you just being hyperbolic

00:05:51.180 --> 00:05:52.950
or do you mean haunted?

00:05:52.950 --> 00:05:54.300
&gt;&gt; Joyce Carol Oates: Well
you can't really write

00:05:54.300 --> 00:05:57.420
or have much art that's
galvanized by emotion

00:05:57.420 --> 00:06:01.430
if you haven't really
identified with it,

00:06:01.430 --> 00:06:05.320
you know in some unconscious way.

00:06:05.320 --> 00:06:08.240
So people all have true stories,

00:06:08.240 --> 00:06:11.850
they have their own true
voice and a true stories.

00:06:11.850 --> 00:06:15.900
And some people come to these
true stories immediately

00:06:15.900 --> 00:06:17.210
when they're young.

00:06:17.210 --> 00:06:19.570
Others have to sort
of work toward it.

00:06:19.570 --> 00:06:21.820
I mean there are very well
known and brilliant writers,

00:06:21.820 --> 00:06:25.330
I think like Tony Morrison
