00:08:56.150 --> 00:08:57.700
You're looking back to literature.

00:08:57.700 --> 00:09:02.090
It's the most traditional of all
the forms is Gothic literature,

00:09:02.090 --> 00:09:05.050
it pays homage to a predecessors.

00:09:05.050 --> 00:09:09.280
You're probably looking back to
Edgar Allan Poe or Lovecraft.

00:09:09.280 --> 00:09:13.180
And so or you might be
looking back to Emily Bronte,

00:09:13.180 --> 00:09:17.920
sort of a little bit of the
Gothic in the Bronte writings.

00:09:17.920 --> 00:09:19.220
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: Yes.

00:09:19.220 --> 00:09:20.520
&gt;&gt; Joyce Carol Oates: So it's
a traditional literature that's

00:09:20.520 --> 00:09:22.910
respectful of predecessors.

00:09:22.910 --> 00:09:25.420
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: And
this attracts you to it?

00:09:25.420 --> 00:09:29.140 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Joyce Carol Oates: Yes I think if
we think of the image of the vampire

00:09:29.140 --> 00:09:34.100
for instance, we are probably
talking in psychological terms

00:09:34.100 --> 00:09:39.130
about a class structure in which
there are people at the bottom,

00:09:39.130 --> 00:09:41.980
disenfranchising and powerless,
they may have been peasants

00:09:41.980 --> 00:09:43.750
in Europe or [inaudible].

00:09:43.750 --> 00:09:48.630
